---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Fundamentals 8 — Maurice Arviso"
  description="Unfolding case study: Oxygenation and Hygiene (FUN-08)"
>

  <div class="breadcrumb">
    <a href={base}>Home</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <a href={`${base}cases/`}>Cases</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <a href={`${base}cases/fundamentals/`}>Fundamentals</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <span>Fundamentals 8 — Maurice Arviso</span>
  </div>

  <div class="case-header">
    <span class="card-tag">Respiratory / Cultural Care</span>
    <h1>Fundamentals 8 — Maurice Arviso</h1>
    <p class="case-subtitle">Oxygenation and Culturally Sensitive Hygiene Care</p>
    <div class="case-meta">
      <span>👤 Maurice Arviso, 60 years, Native American Male</span>
      <span>⏱ Scenario: 20 – 25 minutes</span>
      <span>💬 Debrief: 20 – 25 minutes</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout callout-info">
    <strong>📖 How to Use This Unfolding Case Study</strong>
    <p>Work through each phase in order. Information is revealed progressively — exactly as it would be in a real clinical encounter. Before reading each answer, pause and reason through the question yourself. Use the <strong>▶ Reveal Answer</strong> toggles to check your thinking.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- PHASE 1 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase1">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 1</span>
      <h2>You Arrive at the Bedside</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">You are the morning nurse on a medical-surgical unit. Just before your shift started, Maurice asked his son Jonathan to step out, then accidentally spilled urine on the bed and floor while using the urinal. Maurice is soft-spoken and deeply independent — he does not want to be a "burden."</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📋 Handoff Report</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Patient</th><td>Maurice Arviso</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Age / Gender</th><td>60 years · Male · Native American</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Primary Dx</th><td>Community-acquired pneumonia (CAP)</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Secondary Dx</th><td>Anxiety related to hospital admission</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Code Status</th><td>Full code</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Allergies</th><td>Review MAR</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Key context</th><td>Wife died in hospital 1 yr ago; father died at 55 in hospital — anxious about dying here</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>💊 Current Medications</h3>
        <ul class="med-list">
          <li>Supplemental O₂ (nasal cannula — rate per order)</li>
          <li>Antibiotics IV per order (community-acquired pneumonia)</li>
          <li>Acetaminophen PO PRN (fever and discomfort)</li>
        </ul>
        <h3 style="margin-top:1rem;">🧠 Key Patient Background</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Retired craftsman; makes wooden toys for grandchildren</li>
          <li>Kind-hearted, soft-spoken; tries to do everything independently</li>
          <li>Does not want to be a "burden" to staff — resists asking for help</li>
          <li>Son Jonathan is his primary family support</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>🚪 Entering the Room — What You Observe</h3>
      <p>Maurice is in bed with wet sheets and a wet gown. The urinal is on the floor. He looks deeply embarrassed and will not make direct eye contact. He says quietly: "I am sorry for the trouble." His O₂ is in place. His breathing appears labored.</p>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: How do you respond to Maurice's urine spill in a culturally sensitive way? What is your first priority?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>First: Address the respiratory status (airway is always priority 1).</strong> Then address hygiene and emotional comfort simultaneously.</p>
        <p><strong>Culturally sensitive response to the urine spill:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Approach <strong>calmly and matter-of-factly</strong> — no sighs, no expressions of frustration or surprise</li>
          <li>Do NOT say "How did that happen?" or show any negative reaction</li>
          <li>Say: "Mr. Arviso, accidents happen — let's get you cleaned up and comfortable."</li>
          <li>Close the door; draw the curtain — protect his dignity completely</li>
          <li>Ask: "Would you like Jonathan to come back in, or would you prefer privacy for now?"</li>
          <li><strong>Never shame a patient</strong> — shame prevents patients from asking for help in the future, increasing fall and injury risk</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Cultural context:</strong> In many Native American cultures, silence and reserve do not signal disengagement. Maurice's quietness reflects dignity — not indifference. Respond with quiet, calm competence.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ After addressing Maurice's immediate emotional comfort, you perform your respiratory assessment…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 2 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase2">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 2</span>
      <h2>Respiratory Assessment</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">You quickly assess Maurice's respiratory status. He appears short of breath and is breathing harder than he should be at rest.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📊 Vital Signs</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Temperature</th><td>38.6°C (101.5°F)</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Blood Pressure</th><td>138/86 mmHg</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Heart Rate</th><td>98 bpm</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Respiratory Rate</th><td>22 breaths/min</td></tr>
            <tr><th>SpO₂</th><td><span class="text-danger">91% on 2L nasal cannula</span></td></tr>
            <tr><th>Pain</th><td>3/10 (chest discomfort)</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🫁 Respiratory Findings</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Respiratory rate elevated: 22/min</li>
          <li>Lung sounds: crackles bilateral lower lobes; diminished right base</li>
          <li>Use of accessory muscles — mild intercostal retractions</li>
          <li>Productive cough — yellow-green sputum</li>
          <li>Lips and nail beds: slightly pale; no frank cyanosis</li>
          <li>Patient positioning: sitting forward slightly (tripod position)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: SpO₂ is 91% on 2L O₂. What do you do first? What oxygen device is appropriate?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>SpO₂ 91% = below acceptable threshold (goal ≥ 95%).</strong></p>
        <p><strong>Immediate actions:</strong></p>
        <ol>
          <li>Reposition to <strong>High-Fowler's position (60–90°)</strong> — maximizes diaphragm descent and lung expansion</li>
          <li>Titrate O₂ upward per order — increase nasal cannula to 4L/min</li>
          <li>If no order allows titration: <strong>notify provider immediately</strong></li>
          <li>Reassess SpO₂ after repositioning and O₂ adjustment</li>
        </ol>
        <p><strong>Oxygen device comparison for Maurice:</strong></p>
        <table class="data-table" style="margin-top:0.5rem;">
          <thead><tr><th>Device</th><th>Flow</th><th>FiO₂</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Nasal cannula</td><td>1–6 L/min</td><td>24–44%</td><td>Current device; allows speech and eating</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Simple face mask</td><td>5–10 L/min</td><td>40–60%</td><td>Next step if NC insufficient</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Non-rebreather mask</td><td>10–15 L/min</td><td>60–90%</td><td>Emergency high-flow O₂</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p><strong>Key:</strong> Cyanosis is a LATE sign of hypoxia — do not wait for cyanosis to act. Treat SpO₂ &lt; 95% promptly.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ After improving oxygenation, you proceed to hygiene care…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 3 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase3">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 3</span>
      <h2>Hygiene Care — Bed Bath and Linen Change</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">With Maurice's SpO₂ improving to 94% after repositioning and O₂ increase, you now prepare to provide a bed bath and change his wet linens. Maurice asks quietly if you could close the door completely first.</p>
    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>🛁 Bed Bath and Occupied Bed-Making Steps</h3>
      <table class="data-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Step</th><th>Action</th><th>Rationale</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>1</td><td>Explain the procedure; ask about preferences</td><td>Respects autonomy and cultural values</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2</td><td>Close door; draw curtain completely</td><td>Dignity and privacy — especially important for Maurice</td></tr>
          <tr><td>3</td><td>Gather ALL supplies before beginning</td><td>Prevents leaving patient exposed mid-procedure</td></tr>
          <tr><td>4</td><td>Maintain patient warmth — cover areas not being washed</td><td>Prevent chilling; maintain dignity</td></tr>
          <tr><td>5</td><td>Use warm water; test temperature before contact</td><td>Comfort; prevent burns</td></tr>
          <tr><td>6</td><td>Wash face, neck, arms, trunk, legs in order</td><td>Head-to-toe direction</td></tr>
          <tr><td>7</td><td>Clean perineal area LAST (most contaminated)</td><td>Infection prevention</td></tr>
          <tr><td>8</td><td>Occupied bed change: patient rolls to one side; change half; roll to other side; complete</td><td>Maintains patient safety during linen change</td></tr>
          <tr><td>9</td><td>Apply clean gown; ensure O₂ tubing accessible through gown</td><td>Maintains O₂ therapy throughout</td></tr>
          <tr><td>10</td><td>Dispose of soiled linens per facility policy</td><td>Infection control</td></tr>
          <tr><td>11</td><td>Ensure call light within reach; bed at lowest position</td><td>Safety and fall prevention</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: Maurice resists asking for help generally. What nursing interventions reduce his fall risk?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ul>
          <li>Educate Maurice directly: "It is not a burden to call us — answering your call light is exactly what we are here for."</li>
          <li>Ensure call light is always within easy reach of his dominant hand</li>
          <li>Anticipate his needs — check in proactively so he does not need to initiate</li>
          <li>Bed in lowest position; side rails appropriately positioned</li>
          <li>Non-skid socks on feet</li>
          <li>If Maurice needs the urinal, leave it within reach rather than on a far surface</li>
          <li>Document fall risk; implement fall precautions per facility policy</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ With hygiene care complete, you open a conversation about Maurice's anxiety…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 4 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase4">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 4</span>
      <h2>Cultural Assessment and Therapeutic Communication</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">After hygiene care, Maurice seems more relaxed. He says slowly: "My wife died here. My father too. I am afraid of what this cough means." He becomes silent. He looks out the window. He does not look at you.</p>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: How do you respond therapeutically? What cultural factors are at play?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Therapeutic response:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Do <strong>not</strong> immediately try to reassure or solve the problem — sit quietly for a moment first</li>
          <li>"I hear you, Mr. Arviso. That is a heavy thing to carry. Losing both your wife and your father in a hospital — and now being here yourself."</li>
          <li>Allow silence — silence is therapeutic in many Native American communication styles. Do not rush to fill it.</li>
          <li>Validate: "It makes complete sense that you feel afraid."</li>
          <li>Then gently pivot: "I want you to know that our team is focused on helping you get better and get home to your family."</li>
          <li>Ask: "Are there any spiritual practices or cultural traditions that are important to you while you're here? I want to support what matters to you."</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Cultural considerations — Native American patients:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Indirect eye contact</strong> is respectful — do not interpret the lack of eye contact as disinterest</li>
          <li><strong>Silence is valued</strong> — allow longer pauses; do not interrupt</li>
          <li>Family and community may be central to decision-making — Jonathan should be included when Maurice wishes</li>
          <li>Spiritual connection to nature, ancestors, and the spirit world may be important</li>
          <li>Ask about traditional healers or ceremonies the patient may wish to incorporate</li>
          <li><strong>Never shame or dismiss</strong> cultural practices</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ You reassess Maurice's oxygenation and plan your documentation…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 5 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase5">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 5</span>
      <h2>Ongoing Oxygenation and Breathing Exercises</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">Maurice's SpO₂ has improved to 95% on 4L nasal cannula. You reassess his lung sounds. Crackles remain bilateral lower lobes. He tells you the chest discomfort makes it hard to take deep breaths.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🌬️ Non-Pharmacologic Oxygenation Strategies</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>High-Fowler's position</strong> — maintain 60–90° to maximize diaphragm descent</li>
          <li><strong>Incentive spirometry</strong> — slow, deep inspirations to a goal volume; 10 times/hour while awake</li>
          <li><strong>Deep breathing and coughing</strong> — mobilizes secretions; re-expands atelectatic alveoli</li>
          <li><strong>Adequate hydration</strong> — thins secretions; easier to clear</li>
          <li><strong>Early ambulation</strong> — even a chair-to-chair transfer promotes lung expansion</li>
          <li><strong>Nebulizer treatments</strong> — per order if bronchospasm or mucus retention</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🎯 Goals of Oxygenation Management</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>SpO₂ goal</th><td>≥ 95% (or per provider order)</td></tr>
            <tr><th>RR goal</th><td>12–20 breaths/min</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Breath sounds</th><td>Clear; resolving crackles</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Patient comfort</th><td>Decreased dyspnea; able to speak in full sentences</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: Teaching incentive spirometry to Maurice — how do you adapt your approach?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ul>
          <li>Demonstrate first, then ask Maurice to try</li>
          <li>Use simple, plain language: "Take a slow, deep breath in through this tube — as slowly and as deeply as you can. Hold it for 3 seconds. Then breathe out slowly."</li>
          <li>Set the goal marker at a realistic level; increase gradually</li>
          <li>Encourage without being condescending: "That was a good effort — each time you do it, you're helping your lungs stay healthy."</li>
          <li>Acknowledge that it may be uncomfortable: "I know it might feel hard with the chest discomfort — taking your pain medicine first may make it easier."</li>
          <li>Ask Maurice if he would like Jonathan present for teaching — family reinforcement improves adherence</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ You complete your assessment and prepare SBAR documentation…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 6 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase6">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 6</span>
      <h2>Priority Diagnoses and Documentation</h2>
    </div>
    <h3>📋 Priority Nursing Diagnoses</h3>
    <div class="dx-rank-list">
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">1</span>
        <div><strong>Impaired Gas Exchange</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: SpO₂ 91% on 2L O₂; RR 22; bilateral crackles; diminished right base; productive cough</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">2</span>
        <div><strong>Anxiety</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: Verbalized fear of dying in hospital; history of losing wife and father in hospital; reluctance to ask for help</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">3</span>
        <div><strong>Risk for Falls</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: Getting up independently without calling for help; urine spill while trying to use urinal alone</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">4</span>
        <div><strong>Self-Care Deficit (Hygiene)</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: Soiled bed and gown from urine spill; acute illness limiting self-care ability</div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ SBAR — Calling the Provider About Maurice</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <div class="sbar-block">
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-s"><span class="sbar-label">S — Situation</span><p>Calling about Maurice Arviso, a 60-year-old Native American male admitted with community-acquired pneumonia, with SpO₂ of 91% on 2L nasal cannula this morning.</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-b"><span class="sbar-label">B — Background</span><p>Admitted with CAP; on IV antibiotics, supplemental O₂, and acetaminophen. He has significant anxiety related to fear of dying in the hospital, having lost his wife and father in hospital settings. He resists asking for help, creating fall risk.</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-a"><span class="sbar-label">A — Assessment</span><p>SpO₂ improved to 95% after repositioning to High-Fowler's and increasing O₂ to 4L/min. Lung sounds: crackles bilateral lower lobes, diminished right base. RR 22. Productive cough — yellow-green sputum. Patient is anxious and not performing breathing exercises due to chest discomfort.</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-r"><span class="sbar-label">R — Recommendation</span><p>Requesting: confirmation of O₂ titration order; order for incentive spirometry; social work or patient navigator consult for anxiety and cultural support; review of antibiotic regimen and anticipated hospital course.</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <!-- APPENDIX A: Medications -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="appendix-a">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Appendix A</span>
      <h2>Medication and Oxygen Therapy Review</h2>
    </div>
    <table class="data-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Therapy</th><th>Class / Device</th><th>Key Points</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Supplemental O₂ via Nasal Cannula</strong></td>
          <td>Oxygen delivery</td>
          <td>1–6 L/min; delivers 24–44% FiO₂; allows speech and eating; titrate to SpO₂ ≥ 95% per order</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>IV Antibiotics (CAP-targeted)</strong></td>
          <td>Antibiotic (varies)</td>
          <td>Administer on schedule — consistent levels are essential; monitor for allergic reaction; culture before starting if not already done</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Acetaminophen PO</strong></td>
          <td>Analgesic / Antipyretic</td>
          <td>For fever and discomfort; max 4 g/day (less if liver disease); give before breathing exercises to improve participation</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- APPENDIX B: Q&A -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="appendix-b">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Appendix B</span>
      <h2>Post-Simulation Questions &amp; Answers</h2>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q1: What are the early and late signs of hypoxia?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Early signs:</strong> Restlessness, anxiety, confusion, tachycardia, tachypnea, dyspnea, diaphoresis, use of accessory muscles, SpO₂ &lt; 95%</p>
        <p><strong>Late signs (more serious):</strong> Cyanosis (bluish lips/nails/skin), bradycardia, decreased consciousness, stupor/unresponsiveness, decreased or absent respiratory effort</p>
        <p><strong>Key point:</strong> Cyanosis is a LATE sign — by the time it is visible, the patient is severely hypoxic. Treat early signs aggressively.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q2: What are the three priority nursing diagnoses for Maurice, in order?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Impaired Gas Exchange</strong> — airway and oxygenation are always the first priority; Maurice's SpO₂ was 91%</li>
          <li><strong>Anxiety</strong> — his fear of dying in the hospital directly affects his willingness to accept care and call for help</li>
          <li><strong>Risk for Falls</strong> — demonstrated by his attempt to manage the urinal independently without calling for help</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q3: What cultural considerations apply specifically to Native American patients?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ul>
          <li>Reserved communication style — silence does not indicate disengagement</li>
          <li>Direct eye contact may feel disrespectful — do not insist</li>
          <li>Allow longer pauses in conversation; do not rush to fill silence</li>
          <li>Family and community involvement may be collective rather than individual</li>
          <li>Spiritual practices, traditional healers, and ceremonies may be important — ask respectfully</li>
          <li>Never shame the patient — shame prevents future help-seeking</li>
          <li>Approach as an equal partner — not paternalistic</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q4: When would Maurice need to be escalated to a higher level of care?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ul>
          <li>SpO₂ &lt; 90% despite supplemental oxygen</li>
          <li>Respiratory rate &gt; 30 breaths/min</li>
          <li>Worsening mental status or confusion</li>
          <li>Signs of sepsis: HR &gt; 90, fever or hypothermia, hypotension, altered mentation</li>
          <li>Failure to improve with antibiotics within 48–72 hours</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <!-- APPENDIX C: References -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="appendix-c">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Appendix C</span>
      <h2>References</h2>
    </div>
    <ol class="ref-list">
      <li>Potter, P. A., Perry, A. G., Stockert, P. A., &amp; Hall, A. (2021). <em>Fundamentals of nursing</em> (10th ed.). Elsevier.</li>
      <li>National Congress of American Indians. (2020). <em>Native American/Alaska Native health disparities</em>. NCAI.</li>
      <li>Vallerand, A. H., &amp; Sanoski, C. A. (2021). <em>Davis's drug guide for nurses</em> (17th ed.). F.A. Davis.</li>
    </ol>
    <div style="margin-top: 2rem;">
      <a href={`${base}cases/fundamentals/`} class="btn-back">← Back to Fundamentals</a>
    </div>
  </div>

</BaseLayout>

<style>
  /* ── Phase structure ─────────────────────────────────────────── */
  .case-subtitle {
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    margin-top: 0.25rem;
  }

  .phase-card {
    background: var(--color-surface);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    padding: 2rem;
    margin-bottom: 0;
    box-shadow: var(--shadow);
    border-top: 4px solid var(--color-primary);
  }

  .appendix-card {
    border-top-color: var(--color-secondary);
  }

  .phase-header {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 1rem;
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }

  .phase-header h2 {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: 1.5rem;
  }

  .phase-badge {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    background: var(--color-primary);
    color: #fff;
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
    padding: 0.3rem 0.8rem;
    border-radius: 20px;
    white-space: nowrap;
  }

  .phase-badge-appendix {
    background: var(--color-secondary);
  }

